## Constraints

- A test is discriminating only if at least two hypotheses predict different outcomes for it. A test that all hypotheses agree on cannot eliminate.
- Prefer tests that falsify multiple hypotheses in one observation.
- Every hypothesis must be falsifiable by at least one designed test, or be flagged untestable-by-available-means.
- Do not design a "confirm the favorite" test and call it discriminating — state which hypothesis it would falsify.
- Irreducible pairs survive together; the user must be told the evidence cannot choose between them.
- Rank by elimination power, not by ease of running.
- Do not execute arbitrary Python code in Jinja2 expressions (sandboxed execution).
- Handle missing variables gracefully (leave as-is or use default if specified).

